      Trump Media had a fake auditor?
   =20
 =20

The funniest job in public accounting is now open:

The Securities and Exchange Commission accused the auditor of Donald Trump=
=E2=80=99s social-media company of massive fraud affecting hundreds of comp=
anies and more than 1,500 regulatory filings.
BF Borgers CPA PC and its founder, Benjamin Borgers, will be permanently su=
spended from practicing and appearing as accountants before the SEC, and wi=
ll pay a total of $14 million in fines to settle the probe, the SEC said in=
 a Friday release.
=E2=80=9CBen Borgers and his audit firm, BF Borgers, were responsible for o=
ne of the largest wholesale failures by gatekeepers in our financial market=
s,=E2=80=9D Gurbir Grewal, the SEC=E2=80=99s enforcement chief, said in a s=
tatement. =E2=80=9CBorgers and his firm completely abandoned that role, but=
 thanks to the painstaking work of the SEC staff, Borgers and his sham audi=
t mill have been permanently shut down.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
Trump Media & Technology Group Corp. became a public company in March. Trum=
p Media =E2=80=9Clooks forward to working with new auditing partners in acc=
ordance with today=E2=80=99s SEC order,=E2=80=9D a representative for the c=
ompany said.

I=E2=80=99m kidding, the job isn=E2=80=99t actually open;=C2=A0last week Tr=
ump Media =E2=80=9Cengaged Semple, Marchal & Cooper, LLP (=E2=80=98SMC=E2=
=80=99) as BF Borgers=E2=80=99 replacement.=E2=80=9D Here is the SEC=E2=80=
=99s press release; here is the order shutting down Borgers; here is the SE=
C staff statement on what to do if you are a pubic company that used Borger=
s and now needs to find a different auditor.=20
  [2]

I have said before that, since Trump Media=E2=80=99s financial statements d=
on=E2=80=99t matter=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to its shareholders, to its manager=
s, to its=C2=A0stock price, to its value proposition for its promoters =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0it doesn=E2=80=99t especially matter that Trump Media used a =
=E2=80=9Csham audit mill.=E2=80=9D Still it=E2=80=99s not, you know, good. =
When it turns out that a company has a fake auditor, that raises some quest=
ions. I guess not that many questions. When Trump Media went public, I woul=
d not have=C2=A0guessed=C2=A0that it employed a fake auditor, because I was=
 not aware that that was a thing. But if someone=E2=80=99s going to employ =
a fake auditor, why not Trump Media.
The gist of the SEC case is that BF Borgers =E2=80=94=C2=A0which the Financ=
ial Times reported last month =E2=80=9Cis now the eighth largest audit firm=
 in the country by number of clients,=E2=80=9D while employing only 10 cert=
ified public accountants =E2=80=94=C2=A0was an =E2=80=9Caudit mill.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0The SEC order says that BF Borgers had 350 clients whose financial=
 statements were filed with the SEC, and Ben Borgers himself was the engage=
ment partner for =E2=80=9Cthe overwhelming majority=E2=80=9D of those clien=
ts. He was stretched thin and =E2=80=9Cdid not adequately review or supervi=
se the audit engagements=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0

There were no audit planning meetings held in relation to any of BF Borgers=
=E2=80=99 audit engagements. In addition, Borgers rarely interacted with th=
e staff level auditors. Borgers failed to inform the team members as to the=
 objectives, nature, timing, and extent of the auditing procedures they wer=
e to perform as well as relevant information regarding the particular clien=
t that could affect those procedures. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
As the engagement partner, Borgers also failed both to review the work of t=
he engagement team and to ensure that the workpapers properly and accuratel=
y documented the work performed on the audits.=C2=A0

Instead, they just cut and pasted old audit workpapers into new ones:
Borgers instructed BF Borgers audit staff and contractors to copy workpaper=
s from previous engagements as the final workpapers for new engagements. Sp=
ecifically, audit staff updated the balance sheet date and date of completi=
on on the workpapers, but all of the other information indicating the subst=
antive work done on the engagement was simply copied from the corresponding=
 workpaper from the previous audit or quarterly review. As a result, BF Bor=
gers=E2=80=99 workpapers falsely documented the performance of audit and re=
view procedures and approvals that had not occurred, including falsely repr=
esenting that both Borgers, as the engagement partner, and an EQR [engageme=
nt quality reviewer]=C2=A0reviewed and approved the workpapers.
Look, again, Trump Media=E2=80=99s=C2=A0finances are not especially complic=
ated, and they are not especially important to investors. The stock trades =
on =E2=80=94=C2=A0I mean, at best, it trades on hopes of potential future e=
arnings, though there are=20
other possible explanations for the stock price. But it=E2=80=99s not like =
a one-penny shift in earnings per share is going to have a big effect on th=
e stock.
I suspect it is not alone in this; lots of public companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
not usually big ones =E2=80=94=C2=A0are in similar situations, with simple =
businesses, modest revenues, big dreams, and investors who are not too conc=
erned about the financial statements. Those companies, as a legal matter, n=
eed a certified public accountant to sign off on their financial statements=
, but they don=E2=80=99t need the=C2=A0best=C2=A0accountant; they do not ne=
ed to pay for the name brand and reputation of a well-known accounting firm=
=C2=A0to reassure investors that their finances have been reviewed scrupulo=
usly. It is apparently cheaper to hire an accountant who will review your f=
inances less than scrupulously.=C2=A0Trump Media was arguably in the market=
 for the absolute minimum amount of auditing services, though it managed to=
 buy a bit less than that.

