      Shale
   =20
 =20

=E2=80=9CYou simply could not pay me enough to go to this dinner,=E2=80=9D=
=20
I wrote last week, about a dinner that the Organization of Petroleum Export=
ing Countries (OPEC), the oil cartel, threw for a bunch of US shale oil pro=
ducers, including Scott Sheffield of Pioneer Natural Resources. Just seems =
like a high risk of collusion? Like antitrust regulators would be waiting o=
utside the restaurant with handcuffs? But in fact the dinner was in 2017, a=
nd the antitrust regulators only got around to Sheffield last week. And=C2=
=A0the Financial Times mentions that my scruples are unusual and in fact th=
ere are frequent well-attended OPEC/shale dinners:

Among the evidence the agency cited was a dinner Sheffield attended along w=
ith other US producers, hosted by the late Opec secretary-general Mohammed =
Barkindo, in 2017. Such dinners have become a regular industry feature in r=
ecent years, often hosted on the sidelines of the annual CERAWeek energy co=
nference in Houston.=C2=A0
Attendees say the gatherings have become increasingly cordial in recent yea=
rs as memories fade of the cartel=E2=80=99s efforts to sink the US shale in=
dustry by flooding the market with oil.

I guess one way to tell this story is that once OPEC was the dominant force=
 in oil markets, and kept prices high; then the US shale revolution occurre=
d, and US producers became formidable competitors to OPEC; then OPEC tried =
to fight back by increasing supply to drive down oil prices; and now they a=
re all friends and have cordial dinners together and OPEC keeps supply in c=
heck, while the shale producers also keep supply in check? Maybe that=E2=80=
=99s fine? I hope the food is good.

