ples are unusual and in fact there are frequent well-attended OPEC/shale di=
nners:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the evidence the agency cited was a dinn=
er Sheffield attended along with other US producers, hosted by the late Ope=
c secretary-general Mohammed Barkindo, in 2017. Such dinners have become a =
regular industry feature in recent years, often hosted on the sidelines of =
the annual CERAWeek energy conference in Houston.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Attendees say the gatherings have become incre=
asingly cordial in recent years as memories fade of the cartel=E2=80=99s ef=
forts to sink the US shale industry by flooding the market with oil.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess one way to tell this story is that onc=
e OPEC was the dominant force in oil markets, and kept prices high; then th=
e US shale revolution occurred, and US producers became formidable competit=
ors to OPEC; then OPEC tried to fight back by increasing supply to drive do=
wn oil prices; and now they are all friends and have cordial dinners togeth=
er and OPEC keeps supply in check, while the shale producers also keep supp=
ly in check? Maybe that=E2=80=99s fine? I hope the food is good.</p>
